<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">SNAPCHAT SAYS SORRY <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> Snapchat finally apologized on Thursday for a security vulnerability that allowed a group of security researchers to <b><a href="//lookup.gibsonsec.org/">expose the names and phone numbers</a></b> of 4.6 million Snapchat users on Jan. 1. âWe are sorry for any problems this issue may have caused you and we really appreciate your patience and support,â Snapchat wrote <b><a href="//blog.snapchat.com/post/72768002320/find-friends-improvements">in a blog post.</a></b> (h/t <a href="//www.theverge.com/2014/1/9/5291526/snapchat-updates-app-to-let-users-opt-out-of-contentious-find-friends"><b>The Verge</b></a>)</p>
